{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What Concatenation Does"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "After h attention heads each produce their output, the results must be merged into a single vector before passing to the next layer. The merge strategy is simple concatenation along the feature axis: the d_v-dimensional output of each head is placed end-to-end, producing a h·d_v-dimensional vector. Because d_v = d_model / h, this restores the original d_model dimension:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\text{Concat}(\\text{head}_1, \\ldots, \\text{head}_h) \\in \\mathbb{R}^{n \\times h \\cdot d_v} = \\mathbb{R}^{n \\times d_{\\text{model}}}"}}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "Diagram showing h head outputs being concatenated into a single d_model vector, then projected through W_O, alongside an efficient packed-matmul implementation"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why Concatenation and Not Summation?"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Concatenation is lossless — each head's output occupies its own dedicated block of the output vector. If the heads were instead summed or averaged, information from different heads would mix immediately and any head could cancel another. Concatenation preserves each head's representation as a distinct subspace for W_O to then combine."}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Merge Strategy"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Property"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Used in practice?"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Concatenation"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Lossless; heads stay separate until W_O"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Yes — standard"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Sum"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Immediate mixing; loses per-head structure"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "No"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Mean"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Destroys per-head identity; dilutes signal"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "No"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Output Projection W_O"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "After concatenation the vector is h·d_v = d_model wide. W_O ∈ ℝ^(d_model × d_model) is a learned linear map that "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "mixes information across heads"}, {"type": "text", "text": " and projects back to d_model. Each output neuron in W_O sees all h heads simultaneously, learning to reweight their contributions. Without W_O, the h blocks would remain independent — the model could not learn cross-head interactions."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Shapes at Each Step"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# BERT-base example: d_model=768, h=12, d_k=d_v=64, n=seq_len\nimport torch\n\nbatch, n, d_model, h, d_k = 1, 10, 768, 12, 64\n\n# Each head i produces: (batch, n, d_k) = (1, 10, 64)\nhead_outputs = [torch.randn(batch, n, d_k) for _ in range(h)]\n\n# Step 1: concatenate along feature dim\nconcatenated = torch.cat(head_outputs, dim=-1)  # (1, 10, 768)\nprint(concatenated.shape)   # torch.Size([1, 10, 768])\n\n# Step 2: output projection\nW_O = torch.randn(d_model, d_model)\noutput = concatenated @ W_O  # (1, 10, 768)\nprint(output.shape)          # torch.Size([1, 10, 768])"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Efficient Implementation: Reshape Instead of Cat"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "In practice, separate lists of head outputs are never created. The projections for all heads are packed into one large matrix multiplication, and the concatenation is achieved via a "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "reshape"}, {"type": "text", "text": " / "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "view"}, {"type": "text", "text": ". This avoids Python loops and keeps the entire computation on GPU as a single batched kernel."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\ndef multi_head_attention_packed(X, W_Q, W_K, W_V, W_O, h, mask=None):\n    \"\"\"\n    X:    (batch, n, d_model)\n    W_Q, W_K, W_V: (d_model, d_model)  — packed for all h heads\n    W_O:  (d_model, d_model)\n    \"\"\"\n    batch, n, d_model = X.shape\n    d_k = d_model // h\n\n    # Single matmul for all heads at once\n    Q = X @ W_Q  # (batch, n, d_model)\n    K = X @ W_K\n    V = X @ W_V\n\n    # Reshape to expose the head dimension: (batch, h, n, d_k)\n    def split(t):\n        return t.view(batch, n, h, d_k).transpose(1, 2)\n\n    Q, K, V = split(Q), split(K), split(V)\n\n    # Batched SDPA — processes all h heads in one call\n    ctx = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(Q, K, V,\n                                         attn_mask=mask,\n                                         is_causal=False)\n    # ctx: (batch, h, n, d_k)\n\n    # Concatenation = transpose + reshape\n    ctx = ctx.transpose(1, 2).contiguous().view(batch, n, d_model)\n    # ctx: (batch, n, h * d_k) == (batch, n, d_model)  ← the concat\n\n    return ctx @ W_O   # (batch, n, d_model)\n\n\n# Verify shapes\nbatch, n, d_model, h = 2, 10, 768, 12\nX = torch.randn(batch, n, d_model)\nWQ = torch.randn(d_model, d_model)\nWK = torch.randn(d_model, d_model)\nWV = torch.randn(d_model, d_model)\nWO = torch.randn(d_model, d_model)\n\nout = multi_head_attention_packed(X, WQ, WK, WV, WO, h)\nprint(out.shape)  # torch.Size([2, 10, 768])"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Reshape IS the Concatenation"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "It is worth stating explicitly: the "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": ".transpose(1, 2).contiguous().view(batch, n, d_model)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " at the end is not a separate concat operation — it "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "is"}, {"type": "text", "text": " the concatenation. Because the head dimension (h) and the per-head dimension (d_k) are adjacent in memory after the transpose, flattening them together is mathematically identical to placing the h vectors end-to-end. The GPU never builds a list of separate tensors."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import torch\n\n# Demonstrate equivalence\nbatch, h, n, d_k = 1, 3, 4, 2\nctx = torch.randn(batch, h, n, d_k)\n\n# Method 1: explicit torch.cat\nheads = [ctx[:, i, :, :] for i in range(h)]          # list of (1, n, d_k)\nexplicit_cat = torch.cat(heads, dim=-1)               # (1, n, h*d_k)\n\n# Method 2: reshape (used in practice)\nreshape_cat = ctx.transpose(1, 2).contiguous().view(batch, n, h * d_k)\n\nprint(torch.allclose(explicit_cat, reshape_cat))  # True"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Memory Layout Intuition"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "After "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "ctx.transpose(1, 2)"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", the tensor has shape (batch, n, h, d_k) with heads as the second-to-last axis. The "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": ".contiguous()"}, {"type": "text", "text": " call ensures the data is laid out sequentially in memory: for each token position i, the d_k values from head 1 come first, then head 2's d_k values, and so on. The final "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": ".view(batch, n, h * d_k)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " simply reinterprets this contiguous block as a single h·d_k-dimensional vector per position — the concatenated representation."}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Key insight:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Concatenation preserves each head's output as a distinct block, giving W_O full control over how to blend them. The efficient packed implementation avoids Python loops entirely — all h heads run in one batched GPU kernel, and the concat is a free reshape."}]}]}]}}